WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.210 --> 00:00:02.850
- The internet in Japan looks different.

00:00:02.850 --> 00:00:05.730
In a world of minimalist
designs and large clean images,

00:00:05.730 --> 00:00:07.320
websites in Japan seem to mirror

00:00:07.320 --> 00:00:09.720
the language and culture of their home,

00:00:09.720 --> 00:00:12.180
colorful and a little cramped.

00:00:12.180 --> 00:00:14.760
At least that's according to
a theory I read back in 2013

00:00:14.760 --> 00:00:17.070
and have shared with a
bunch of people since.

00:00:17.070 --> 00:00:18.540
There's just one problem.

00:00:18.540 --> 00:00:22.470
I don't know if it's
true, so let's fix that.

00:00:22.470 --> 00:00:24.840
In this video, we use an AI to figure out

00:00:24.840 --> 00:00:27.570
what's so special about
Japanese web design

00:00:27.570 --> 00:00:30.930
and how even across an
ocean it impacts you today.

00:00:30.930 --> 00:00:32.010
I think I might give up.

00:00:32.010 --> 00:00:34.410
Thank you to Hostinger
for sponsoring this video.

00:00:34.410 --> 00:00:36.030
Let's start off with how I realized

00:00:36.030 --> 00:00:38.430
that I may have been lying to
people for the past decade.

00:00:38.430 --> 00:00:40.890
I was setting up a website
to document an old project.

00:00:40.890 --> 00:00:42.240
While scrolling through the templates,

00:00:42.240 --> 00:00:44.670
the following three thoughts
passed through my head.

00:00:44.670 --> 00:00:47.370
One, "Wow, these themes
are really minimalist."

00:00:47.370 --> 00:00:50.580
Two, "Remember how Japan, a
nation known for minimalism,

00:00:50.580 --> 00:00:53.310
ironically has really cluttered webpages?"

00:00:53.310 --> 00:00:56.100
And three, "How did I know that?"

00:00:56.100 --> 00:00:57.210
Has that ever happened to you?

00:00:57.210 --> 00:00:59.040
Like you accept something
as fact when you're a kid,

00:00:59.040 --> 00:01:01.950
but now that your prefrontal
cortex has finished developing,

00:01:01.950 --> 00:01:04.080
you think back and you're like,

00:01:04.080 --> 00:01:06.060
hold on, my spider sense is tingling.

00:01:06.060 --> 00:01:08.250
What could possibly be
so special about Japan

00:01:08.250 --> 00:01:11.010
that they just decide to have
different web design practices

00:01:11.010 --> 00:01:13.260
than the rest of the world apparently?

00:01:13.260 --> 00:01:16.740
And even if the article was
true, it came out 10 years ago.

00:01:16.740 --> 00:01:19.590
I don't know if it's still
true. This is the internet.

00:01:19.590 --> 00:01:21.360
Twitter was normal one day

00:01:21.360 --> 00:01:23.790
and then it might be dead
by the time you watch this,

00:01:23.790 --> 00:01:24.623
to be honest.

00:01:24.623 --> 00:01:25.860
The internet moves fast.

00:01:25.860 --> 00:01:29.310
So in this video, I wanna put
the theory to a modern test.

00:01:29.310 --> 00:01:31.080
I wanna see if there is something unique

00:01:31.080 --> 00:01:34.830
about Japanese web design,
and if there is, why?

00:01:34.830 --> 00:01:36.330
Am I just overcompensating

00:01:36.330 --> 00:01:38.853
because I realize I've
been doing misinformation?

00:01:39.750 --> 00:01:41.490
Probably.

00:01:41.490 --> 00:01:42.720
Let's do this.

00:01:42.720 --> 00:01:44.640
So I tweeted this, "Are you in Asia?

00:01:44.640 --> 00:01:45.870
Have you been using the internet

00:01:45.870 --> 00:01:47.610
over the past 5 to 10 years?

00:01:47.610 --> 00:01:48.443
Please hit me up."

00:01:48.443 --> 00:01:50.460
And it worked, my DMs
are completely destroyed,

00:01:50.460 --> 00:01:52.830
but I have been chatting with
a bunch of awesome people

00:01:52.830 --> 00:01:56.100
and no one really knows
what I'm talking about.

00:01:56.100 --> 00:01:58.530
I am so worried this
video's gonna go nowhere.

00:01:58.530 --> 00:02:00.870
I took those replies to mean
that this web design thing

00:02:00.870 --> 00:02:03.540
really might just be isolated to Japan.

00:02:03.540 --> 00:02:04.980
So I decided to verify

00:02:04.980 --> 00:02:07.320
by checking out the most popular websites

00:02:07.320 --> 00:02:08.820
in every country in the world.

00:02:08.820 --> 00:02:11.550
So many of these websites are just Google

00:02:11.550 --> 00:02:13.110
or manga reading websites.

00:02:13.110 --> 00:02:15.750
Are we just all weebs
who don't know things?

00:02:15.750 --> 00:02:18.210
I categorized the websites
based on their contents.

00:02:18.210 --> 00:02:20.100
Okay, I know that this
shouldn't surprise me,

00:02:20.100 --> 00:02:24.180
but the internet is full of
a lot of not great stuff.

00:02:24.180 --> 00:02:25.800
Just looking at some of these categories,

00:02:25.800 --> 00:02:30.480
we've got explicit, illegal,
spam, suspected malware.

00:02:30.480 --> 00:02:32.400
I'm just gonna whoop.

00:02:32.400 --> 00:02:35.580
I then accessed each website
using a web crawler and a VPN

00:02:35.580 --> 00:02:37.620
to take screenshots of the local page.

00:02:37.620 --> 00:02:39.030
So because of GDPR,

00:02:39.030 --> 00:02:42.060
websites will ask you if you
want cookies, which I respect,

00:02:42.060 --> 00:02:46.080
except that popup blocks
the entire freaking webpage.

00:02:46.080 --> 00:02:46.950
So I need to figure out

00:02:46.950 --> 00:02:48.900
how to say accept cookies or allow cookies

00:02:48.900 --> 00:02:53.070
or, okay, cool, cookies in every language.

00:02:53.070 --> 00:02:55.350
I thought computers were
supposed to make things easy.

00:02:55.350 --> 00:02:56.700
Just look at this.

00:02:56.700 --> 00:02:58.830
Also, the way that they've implemented

00:02:58.830 --> 00:03:00.060
these buttons are different.

00:03:00.060 --> 00:03:01.440
So I don't just need to know the language,

00:03:01.440 --> 00:03:04.920
I need to find the specific
button element to click

00:03:04.920 --> 00:03:06.600
and then code it in.

00:03:06.600 --> 00:03:07.710
I think I might give up.

00:03:07.710 --> 00:03:12.710
Okay, so I now have 2,671 screenshots

00:03:12.810 --> 00:03:15.450
of websites across like 200 countries.

00:03:15.450 --> 00:03:17.280
Ideally, I'd like to know how each website

00:03:17.280 --> 00:03:19.350
compares to every other website,

00:03:19.350 --> 00:03:20.850
but that would mean doing like

00:03:23.280 --> 00:03:25.410
3 million comparisons.

00:03:25.410 --> 00:03:28.200
My brain is too soft and small to do that,

00:03:28.200 --> 00:03:30.090
but luckily we have computers.

00:03:30.090 --> 00:03:31.560
So I ended up using machine learning

00:03:31.560 --> 00:03:33.060
to extract the most prominent features

00:03:33.060 --> 00:03:34.500
of each website screenshot.

00:03:34.500 --> 00:03:36.600
I then compared those
extractions to one another

00:03:36.600 --> 00:03:39.090
using a statistical method
of dimensionality reduction

00:03:39.090 --> 00:03:41.790
called t-distributed
stochastic neighbor embeddings.

00:03:41.790 --> 00:03:42.623
Please come back.

00:03:42.623 --> 00:03:44.400
All you need to know is
that this lets us see

00:03:44.400 --> 00:03:48.420
how our AI organizes and
groups our website screenshots.

00:03:48.420 --> 00:03:50.130
The closer it puts screenshots together,

00:03:50.130 --> 00:03:51.840
the more similar their designs,

00:03:51.840 --> 00:03:54.090
and the further apart
means more dissimilar.

00:03:54.090 --> 00:03:54.923
That's all I'm doing.

00:03:54.923 --> 00:03:57.570
So now let's run this.

00:03:57.570 --> 00:03:59.670
Kind of anti-climactic.

00:03:59.670 --> 00:04:02.130
So this is how the AI
organized our websites.

00:04:02.130 --> 00:04:04.740
So many pictures, so little resolution.

00:04:04.740 --> 00:04:05.573
But if you look closely,

00:04:05.573 --> 00:04:07.140
there are clumps that
have started to form.

00:04:07.140 --> 00:04:09.840
We've got Facebook, Google,

00:04:09.840 --> 00:04:12.270
websites that would not let me in.

00:04:12.270 --> 00:04:14.340
Twitter and Wikipedia.

00:04:14.340 --> 00:04:15.173
But the thing is,

00:04:15.173 --> 00:04:17.760
is that these websites are
more exception than the rule.

00:04:17.760 --> 00:04:20.130
They aren't representative
of any nation's design style

00:04:20.130 --> 00:04:22.710
because they are in
basically every nation.

00:04:22.710 --> 00:04:24.090
So I'm not gonna care about them.

00:04:24.090 --> 00:04:27.960
Instead, what I do care
about is this thing,

00:04:27.960 --> 00:04:31.800
what I like to call the clump of interest.

00:04:31.800 --> 00:04:33.480
If we look closely at this clump,

00:04:33.480 --> 00:04:36.960
we can see that it's
sorted along two axes.

00:04:36.960 --> 00:04:39.570
Vertically, it's pretty obvious,
it goes from dark to light,

00:04:39.570 --> 00:04:43.590
but horizontally, you probably can't tell

00:04:43.590 --> 00:04:44.580
because you can't see anything.

00:04:44.580 --> 00:04:45.413
But on the left side,

00:04:45.413 --> 00:04:47.310
we've got images with
a lot of empty space,

00:04:47.310 --> 00:04:49.350
a little bit of text, very simple images.

00:04:49.350 --> 00:04:50.310
As we move to the middle,

00:04:50.310 --> 00:04:53.730
we have larger images and two
or three columns of content.

00:04:53.730 --> 00:04:55.380
But finally, as we move
furthest to the right,

00:04:55.380 --> 00:04:56.730
we have a lot going on.

00:04:56.730 --> 00:04:59.280
A whole bunch of columns,
really tiny images,

00:04:59.280 --> 00:05:02.370
often of content that I cannot show you.

00:05:02.370 --> 00:05:03.900
I tried so hard to filter.

00:05:03.900 --> 00:05:06.330
The internet just has so much...

00:05:06.330 --> 00:05:07.320
I'm sorry.

00:05:07.320 --> 00:05:10.470
Anyway, those are the visual
patterns that guide this clump.

00:05:10.470 --> 00:05:12.810
Now, where does Japan fit in?

00:05:12.810 --> 00:05:13.643
Oh, yeah, I've just changed

00:05:13.643 --> 00:05:15.240
all the screenshots to little circles

00:05:15.240 --> 00:05:17.850
to make it easier to
see things more clearly.

00:05:17.850 --> 00:05:19.890
So, Japan, ta-dah.

00:05:19.890 --> 00:05:20.940
It's the red dots.

00:05:20.940 --> 00:05:22.620
We've got a little Google over there.

00:05:22.620 --> 00:05:23.453
Right off the bat,

00:05:23.453 --> 00:05:25.980
we can see that it kind of
avoids this sector up here,

00:05:25.980 --> 00:05:28.800
but we don't know if that
is a common distribution.

00:05:28.800 --> 00:05:30.840
Maybe a bunch of other
countries avoid this corner.

00:05:30.840 --> 00:05:31.680
We need to compare.

00:05:31.680 --> 00:05:35.160
So let's see how it compares
against the United States,

00:05:35.160 --> 00:05:39.810
Canada, the UK, Ukraine,
Indonesia, Mexico.

00:05:39.810 --> 00:05:40.650
Are you seeing this?

00:05:40.650 --> 00:05:43.980
All of the countries have
wide varieties of web design

00:05:43.980 --> 00:05:45.300
except for Japan.

00:05:45.300 --> 00:05:47.670
Japan seems to be avoiding this sector

00:05:47.670 --> 00:05:51.060
that is defined by dark, empty spaces.

00:05:51.060 --> 00:05:52.590
In other words, Japan's websites

00:05:52.590 --> 00:05:56.580
are brightly colored and dense,
just like the theory claims.

00:05:56.580 --> 00:05:58.110
Did I just prove something?

00:05:58.110 --> 00:06:00.750
I'm genuinely surprised
that we found something.

00:06:00.750 --> 00:06:03.270
I just wish you could see it better.

00:06:03.270 --> 00:06:04.770
Oh, wait, you can.

